'''''Life & Death''''' is a [[Video game|computer game]] published in 1988 by [[The Software Toolworks]]. The player takes the role of an [[Abdomen|abdominal]] [[surgeon]]. The original packaging for the game included a surgical mask and gloves.<ref name=macworld /> A sequel, ''[[Life & Death II: The Brain]]'', was published in 1990. In this sequel, the player is a [[neurosurgeon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/saturday-crapshoot-life-and-death/ |title=Saturday Crapshoot: Life and Death |date=August 27, 2011 |accessdate=September 11, 2019 |first=Richard |last=Cobbett |website=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref>

==Gameplay==

In the role of a resident abdominal surgeon at fictional hospital Toolworks General, the player must [[Diagnosis|diagnose]] and [[Therapy|treat]] a variety of maladies including [[kidney stones]], [[arthritis]], [[appendicitis]], and [[Aortic aneurysm|aneuritic aorta]]. The last two require the player to perform surgery.

== Reception ==
[[File:Life-&-Death-game-screenshot.png|thumb|left|''Life & Death'' emphasized realism and visual detail even with limited colors.]]

''[[Compute!]]'' complimented ''Life & Death''{{'}}s graphics and sound, stating that the game effectively used [[Color Graphics Adapter|CGA]]'s four colors and the [[PC speaker]], and stated that the game's warning to those queasy of blood was accurate.<ref name="latimer198905">{{cite magazine| title=Life & Death | magazine=[[Compute!]] | issue=108 | date=May 1989 | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-05-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_108_1989_May#page/n71/mode/2up | accessdate=24 April 2016 | last=Latimer | first=Joey | pages=71–72}}</ref> An author on ''[[Gamasutra]]'' praised the game for its attention to detail and the way it offers significant depth and challenge despite only the mouse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/169441/Opinion_A_matter_of_Life__Death.php|title="A Matter Of Life And Death", Leigh Alexander.|publisher=gamasutra.com|accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref>

''[[Macworld]]'' reviewed the Macintosh version of ''Life & Death'', noting its gore and level of difficulty, stating that "If the embossed photo of a bloody brain on the box doesn't get to you, the challenge and frustration of playing the game just might." ''Macworld'' praises ''Life & Death's'' difficulty and educational value, but criticized the "annoying" copy protection, monochrome graphics, and lack of a save function. The reviewer for ''Macworld'' is stated to be a [[doctor of medicine]].<ref name=macworld>{{cite magazine|last = Franklin N. Tessler |first = M.D.|title = Life & Death 1.01 Review|date = March 1990|url = https://archive.org/details/MacWorld_9003_March_1990/page/n195|magazine = Macworld|publisher = Mac Publishing|pages = 182–184}}</ref>

''Life & Death'' was nominated for [[Software Publishers Association]] (SPA) awards for Best Game, Best Simulation and Best Use of Technology.{{citation needed|date=June 2023}}

